http://dbpedia.org/property/desc.value: The cargo ship ran aground on Muckle Skerry, in the Pentland Firth, Scotland. All fifty on board survived.
The decommissioned boom defence vessel was sunk as a naval gunnery target in False Bay off Simon's Town, South Africa.
The 39-gross register ton,  barge sank off Seldovia, Alaska.
The 8-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Naknek, Alaska.
The 7-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire in Taku Inlet in Southeast Alaska.
The 8-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank in Sumner Strait in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska.

The coastal tanker, loaded with gasoline, collided with the American C2 cargo ship Lucile Bloomfield off Le Havre and immediately caught fire, the burning wreck drifted and came ashore near Octeville where it was later scuttled. Seven occupants of the small tanker lost their lives while the Lucile Bloomfield crew escaped unharmed.
The cargo ship ran aground  north of Mukho, South Korea . She broke in two three days later, a total loss.

Chinese Civil War: Battle of Chongwu: The Zhen Nan-class minesweeper was damaged by shelling by People's Liberation Army Navy patrol ships and then was torpedoed by the motor torpedo boat  . She was then beached on Magong Island to prevent her from sinking.
The cargo ship collided with   and sank in the Saint Lawrence River, Canada. One of her fourteen crew was killed and two were reported missing.
Wrecked at Rolvsøy.
The  coastal tanker was sunk as a target in the Black Sea.
The cargo ship sank in the Bay of Biscay whilst under tow following the loss of her rudder. The accident was caused by her cargo shifting.
The Liberty ship caught fire and was abandoned in the Mediterranean Sea . She was towed to Cartagena, Spain where she was declared a constructive total loss.
The 179-gross register ton,  tug sank in Cook Inlet on the south-central coast of Alaska. Her entire crew of 10 survived.
The 10-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by a storm at Uyak  on the coast of Kodiak Island in Alaska.

The  fishing vessel was wrecked on Left Cape  at the entrance to Kiliuda Bay  on the coast of Alaska's Kodiak Island after her helmsman fell asleep at her wheel. Her bottom eventually was damaged beyond repair. Her wreck was visible on Left Cape for decades afterward.
The Liberty ship broke in two and foundered in the Pacific Ocean .
The Liberty ship foundered in the Pacific Ocean
The bulk carrier was wrecked off the Faja Grande Lighthouse, Flores Island, Azores, Portugal. She was on a voyage from New Orleans, Louisiana, United States to Hamburg, West Germany.

The package carrier exploded and sank at Montreal, Quebec after an unbalanced load caused the ship to capsize, letting aerosolized calcium chloride powder to become exposed to water. The ship was raised and returned to service in May 1966.
The cargo ship's cargo of fertilizer caught fire. The ship later capsized and sank in the Atlantic, with three of her 44 crew reported missing.   rescued the other 41 crew.
The 39-gross register ton,  barge was destroyed by a storm at Old Sitka in Southeast Alaska.
The Liberty ship ran aground at Muroran, Hokkaido, Japan. She was declared a constructive total loss.
Chinese Civil War: The Zhen Nan-class minesweeper was sunk off the South China coast by a People's Liberation Army Navy escort vessel.
The cargo ship caught fire off Canvey Island, Essex whilst laden with explosives. Ship flooded during firefighting operations.
The cargo ship sank in the Pacific  north west of Honolulu, Hawaii. All 30 crew rescued by Maria and taken to Japan.
thumb|Catala, 1976The passenger ship was wrecked in a storm at Ocean Shores, Washington, United States.

The  side trawler was lost in the Bering Sea between the Pribilof Islands and Saint Matthew Island approximately  northwest of Saint Paul Island during a severe storm. Fourteen crew members apparently died aboard each of the three Soviet trawlers lost during the day; two trawlers sank, and the third was found capsized with one crew member – the sole survivor from the three trawlers – clinging to it.
The passenger liner burned and sank in the Atlantic Ocean off Miami, Florida, with the loss of 90 lives.
The tanker exploded and caught fire at Mururan, Japan. Three of her crew were killed, 22 were injured, five others reported missing.
The cruise ship ran aground off Stockholm, Sweden. All 94 passengers returned to Stockholm by a Swedish ship.
Chinese Civil War: Battle of Dongshan: The Chien Men-class patrol ship was damaged by Red Chinese patrol ships and then was torpedoed and sunk south of Quemoy by   .
Sank after a collision with a hopper barge. Ten crew were rescued by the tug Danube VIII, but nine others died. Raised in 1966.

Under tow by the tug Tawakoni  after losing her propeller in the North Pacific Ocean  south of Adak, Alaska, the converted Liberty ship was wrecked on Great Sitkin Island in the Aleutian Islands with the loss of one crew member after her towline parted during a storm and she drifted ashore. United States Navy helicopters rescued the rest of her crew.
The 7-gross register ton,  motor vessel sank at Port Lions, Alaska.

The 73-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was wrecked at the head of "American Bay" – probably American Bay on Dall Island in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska, but possibly American Bay on the Alaska Peninsula – in Alaska.
The Liberty ship was driven ashore on Ameland, Friesland, Netherlands. She was declared a constructive total loss in 1970.
The 13-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was crushed by ice and sank near Ketchikan, Alaska.

While towing a  barge from Seward to Cold Bay, Alaska, the 141-gross register ton,  motor tug burned near "Otter Island" – probably a reference to Outer Island  – in Nuka Bay on the south-central coast of Alaska after an engine room fire spread out of control. Her crew of four abandoned ship in a skiff and rowed to the barge, from which the buoy tender   rescued them.
A storm destroyed the 13-gross register ton,  fishing vessel at Carroll Inlet  in Southeast Alaska.
The 57-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Japanese Bay  on the coast of Kodiak Island. The fishing vessel Brisk  rescued her entire crew of three.
Ran aground at Masirah, Oman. Declared a constructive total loss.
The 11-gross register ton  fishing vessel sank in Monashka Bay  on the south-central coast of Alaska.
The 16-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Gould Island  off Prince of Wales Island in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska.
The Liberty ship ran aground at New Caledonia, a total loss.

The 7,252-gross register ton,  Liberty ship was wrecked in heavy seas on rocks at Cape Pankof on the east coast of Unimak Island in the Aleutian Islands. Her crew survived and was evacuated by helicopter and breeches buoy to the medium endurance cutter   and the tug Adeline Foss .
The cargo ship was driven ashore at Ter Heijde, Netherlands. All 49 crew rescued. The ship was declared at constructive total loss and scrapped in situ.
The Liberty ship ran aground on Wolf Island in the Saint Lawrence River and was abandoned. She was declared a constructive total loss.
The 15-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by a storm at Ouzinkie, Alaska.
The 38-gross register ton,  barge was destroyed by fire at Kenai, Alaska.
The Liberty ship sank in the Arabian Sea off Abd al Kuri, South Yemen. Crew abandoned ship and landed on the island, from where their distress calls were answered by RAF Shackleton aircraft and  .
The coaster sank  off Cherbourg, the loss of six of her 25 crew.

The 40-gross register ton,  tug was destroyed off Rocky Point in Bechevin Bay  on the coast of Atka Island in the Aleutian Islands by a fire that broke out in her engine room. Her crew of three abandoned ship in a skiff and survived.
The 12-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank in Cook Inlet approximately  north of Anchor Point, Alaska.
The Liberty ship sank in the Atlantic Ocean off Cape Race, Newfoundland, Canada .
The Liberty ship ran aground on Castle Island, Bahamas. She was later refloated and towed to Philadelphia, Pennsylvania, United States where she was declared at constructive total loss.
The tug sank during a storm in the Bay of Manquemapu,  south of Corral, Chile, with the loss of 51 men while trying to assist Leucotón, which had run aground.
Vietnam War: The blockade runner was scuttled with demolition charges that blew the ship in two in Vu Rung Bay, South Vietnam, while she was under attack by a Douglas A-1 Skyraider aircraft.
The coaster ran aground off the Mull of Kintyre, Scotland. Refloated the next day.
The passenger ship capsized and sank at Bremerhaven.
The 94-gross register ton motor vessel sank at "Segum Island," probably Seguam Island in the Andreanof Islands group in the Aleutian Islands.
The 8-gross register ton  wooden fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Naknek, Alaska.
Vietnam War: The Type 55A gunboat was sunk by Douglas AD-6 and United States Air Force Republic F-105 Thunderchief aircraft at Song Gianh, South Vietnam.
The 12-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Naknek, Alaska.
The ocean liner ran aground off Cherbourg, France but was refloated undamaged shortly afterwards.
The tanker was driven ashore and wrecked at Rio Haina.

The riverboat, operating as an entertainment venue, sank on the Mississippi River at St. Louis, Missouri, during the spring flood. Her steel hull was refloated and put into service as a landing barge for a new stationary showboat, also named Becky Thatcher .
The 7-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank near Saint Joseph Island  in Southeast Alaska.
The tanker collided with Arizona   south of Tokyo and sank with the loss of 18 crew.
The Liberty ship was driven ashore on Great Sitkin Island, Alaska, United States. She was abandoned as a constructive total loss.
The 2,065-ton collier wrecked on Nolleplaat sandbank, off Vlissingen, Zeeland, Netherlands.
thumb|right|USS Frank Knox aground.The  ran aground in the South China Sea on Pratas Reef near Pratas Island. She was salvaged and repaired and eventually returned to service.
The motor vessel was destroyed by fire  north of Sitka, Alaska.
The Liberty ship was abandoned  north of Cochin, India. She sank the next day.

During a voyage from Juneau to Kodiak, Alaska, the 196-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was last heard from on this date while in the Gulf of Alaska off Cape Saint Elias on the southwest end of Kayak Island on the south-central coast of Alaska. She then disappeared with the loss of her entire five-man crew.
The cargo ship ran aground off Hong Kong and broke up. All 41 crew rescued.
The cargo ship foundered in the North Atlantic Ocean  east of Cape Fear, North Carolina, after her cargo shifted.
The 10-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank at Grave Island  off Hoonah, Alaska.
Vietnam War:  The Type 55A gunboat was sunk by aircraft at Lach Troung, South Vietnam. Seven crewmen were killed.
The 9-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Naknek, Alaska.
The Liberty ship broke in two in the Atlantic Ocean . The bow section sank that day, the stern section sank the next day.
The Liberty ship was driven ashore at Wakayama, Japan in a typhoon. She was declared a constructive total loss.
The Liberty ship ran aground off Necochea, Argentina. Declared a constructive total loss, she was subsequently scrapped.
The sealer foundered in the Norwegian Sea. She was on a voyage from the West Ice to Ålesund.
The steam cargo ship caught fire in the English Channel, becoming a total loss.
The cargo ship sank in the Ionian Sea, all 30 crew rescued.
The tug capsized and sank in Chamais Bay with the loss of all six crew.
The ship struck the Grunes de L’Ouest rocks  between Guernsey and Jersey Channel Islands. 40 people were rescued by the Guernsey lifeboat.
The motor vessel sank off Baranof Island in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska.
The fishing trawler sank during a gale in the Bering Sea between Saint Matthew Island and the Pribilof Islands with the loss of her entire crew of 14.
The fishing vessel grounded on a shoal and sank with the loss of two lives near Channel Light 32A in Wrangell Narrows in the Alexander Archipelago in Southeast Alaska.
The 32-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was lost off Kodiak, Alaska.
The tanker exploded and caught fire at Bandar Mashar, Iran, killing 30 of her 41 crew, and two others onshore. The ship capsized and sank in shallow water.
Became stranded and sank on a voyage from Kopervik and Kristiansund.
The 10-gross register ton,  fishing vessel suffered an explosion, burned, and sank at Sitka, Alaska.
The bulk carrier sank after colliding with Topdalsfjord  in the Straits of Mackinac  east of the Mackinac Bridge, killing 10 of her 35 crew members.
The tanker ran aground in Boston Harbor, Massachusetts.
Vietnam War: The Type 55A gunboat was sunk by aircraft at Ben Thuy, South Vietnam.
The lighthouse tender, a converted naval tugboat, was wrecked during a storm in the Bahia San Pedro,  south of Corral, Chile, when her anchor chain broke.
The 7-gross register ton,  motor vessel was destroyed by a storm at St. Michael, Alaska.
A storm destroyed the 8-gross register ton  fishing vessel at Port Moller , Alaska.
The ocean liner ran aground in Southampton Water. Refloated undamaged after 4½ hours.
The 8-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at the Arctic Maid Fisheries warehouse at Naknek, Alaska.
The decommissioned training ship was sunk as a target off "Rosenort".
The 332-ton collier sank in Belfast Lough.
The tanker collided with   in the English Channel. Both ships caught fire and there was a large spill of oil.
The 9-gross register ton,  fishing vessel collided with an unidentified object and was lost in Sukoi Bay north of Cape Douglas  in Cook Inlet on the south-central coast of Alaska.
The cargo ship ran aground at Falsterbo, Sweden and broke in two. Declared a constructive total loss. Refloated in July 1968, cargo discharged and subsequently scrapped the following month.
The cargo ship collided with  : and sank in the English Channel  off Folkestone, Kent with the loss of one of the fifteen crew.
The dredger capsized and sank off Clacton-on-Sea, Essex with the loss of four of her seven crew.
The motor vessel was destroyed by fire on the Copper River Flats southeast of Cordova, Alaska.
A storm destroyed the motor vessel in Southeast Alaska in Shakan Strait  on the northwest coast of Prince of Wales Island in the Alexander Archipelago.
The coastal tanker collided with   and sank in the Scheldt with the loss of four crew.
The Liberty ship ran aground north of Ameland, Friesland, the Netherlands and was wrecked. All 33 crew rescued.
The Victory ship was driven ashore at Bermuda in a storm.
The 114-gross register ton,  barge was destroyed by a storm near St. Michael, Alaska.
The 8-gross register ton,  motor cargo vessel sank in the small boat harbor at Juneau, Alaska.
The 9-gross register ton,  fishing vessel was destroyed by fire at Klawock, Alaska.
The cargo ship ran aground in the River Thames and Gravesend, Kent in fog.
The 14-gross register ton,  fishing vessel sank at Whale Pass, Alaska.
The Liberty ship ran aground in the Sakhalin Islands, Soviet Union and broke in two, a total loss.
The cargo ship foundered while under tow off Cape Villano, Spain.
The T-class submarine collided with   in the English Channel  south of Portland Bill, Dorset.
The Liberty ship struck a reef and was beached . She was refloated but declared a constructive total loss and subsequently scrapped.
Chinese Civil War: Battle of Dongshan: The Qing Jiong-class submarine chaser was shelled and sunk south of Quemoy by  .
The Liberty ship struck a submerged object off the coast of Brazil  and sprang a leak. She was declared a constructive total loss.
The coaster sank in Belfast Lough. All crew rescued.
Collided with   in the River Scheldt near Vlissingen. Repaired and returned to service.
